Health-related quality of life, quality-adjusted life years, and 
quality-adjusted life expectancy in new york city from 1995 to 2006.

Lubetkin EI(1), Jia H.

Author information:
(1)Department of Community Health and Social Medicine, Sophie Davis School of 
Biomedical Education at The City College of New York, 160 Convent Avenue, H404B, 
New York, NY 10031, USA. lubetkin@med.cuny.edu

We applied our previously developed estimation equation to predict EQ-5D index 
scores from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's Healthy Days 
measures for the New York City (NYC) adult population from 1995 to 2006 and 
compared these trends over time with the US general population. Such scores 
enabled us to examine the burden of disease attributable to smoking and 
overweight/obesity at both the local and national levels. We employed the 
estimation equation to the 1993-2007 Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System 
(BRFSS) data to obtain EQ-5D index scores for all survey respondents based on 
their age, self-rated health status, and overall number of unhealthy days. With 
the combination of mortality data, we calculated trends of quality-adjusted life 
years (QALYs), life expectancy (LE), and quality-adjusted life expectancy (QALE) 
as well as the percent of QALYs and QALE lost contributed by smoking and 
overweight/obesity. Mean EQ-5D index scores for NYC adults decreased from 0.874 
to 0.852 but, more recently, have increased to 0.869. The LE of an 18-year-old 
living in NYC increased 4.7 years and QALE increased 2.6 years. The contribution 
of smoking to the proportion of QALYs lost decreased from 6.7% to 3.5%, while 
the contribution of overweight/obesity to the proportion of QALYs lost increased 
from 4.5% to 16.9%. The proportion of QALEs lost due to smoking decreased from 
5.5% to 4.5%, while the proportion of QALEs lost due to overweight/obesity 
increased from 3.5% to 11.8%. Because the Healthy Days measures have been 
included in the BRFSS since 1993, translating Healthy Days Measures to a 
preference-based measure is a useful method for longitudinal tracking of 
population health at the local, state, and national level.

