Medical demography and epidemiology: dizygotic twins.

Bonneux LG(1).

Author information:
(1)Netherlands Interdisciplinary Demographic Institute, NIDI, P.O. Box 11650, 
2502 AR, Den Haag, The Netherlands. bonneux@nidi.nl

Demography is the statistical study of populations, epidemiology of health of 
populations. Fascinating challenges for future research, shared by epidemiology 
and demography, are to be found in the human life course, how the life course is 
transmitted over generations, how the healthy life is shaped by dynamics within 
the life course and how the life course is affected by the social and economic 
environment. The life course begins when two future parents meet. Then social 
disadvantage or privilege is beginning and diverse rates of ageing are being 
fixed. Health in utero and at young age will co-determine health at middle and 
old age, among others mediated by a greater intelligence and a better education. 
Particularly better education compresses cognitive disability at the end of 
life, building cognitive reserves that increase brain plasticity and enhance 
resistance to damage. While with extended life spans may come extended life 
spans with disability, the twin demography and epidemiology may show how to 
lighten the burden of senescence at the end of life.

